+Heraclitus (c. 535–475 BCE — roughly contemporary with Pythagoras) used the term Logos for the single rational principle underlying the apparent chaos of sensory experience. His famous claim — "You cannot step into the same river twice" — is not a lament about change. It is a statement about the Logos: the river changes at every moment, but the *principle* of the river — the structured way in which water flows — is constant. The Logos is constant. The world it organizes is in flux.
+
+The Stoics developed this into a full cosmological account: the Logos is the rational principle immanent in all of reality, the organizing structure through which the universe maintains its coherence. Marcus Aurelius, writing his *Meditations* as the practical notebook of a Stoic emperor: "You have power over your mind, not outside events. Realize this, and you will find strength" — but the full Stoic background is that the mind's power comes from its participation in the universal Logos. The mind that operates according to reason operates in alignment with the structure of reality.
